---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="Signs of Termites Darwin | 9 Indicators to Check Today | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="The nine specific signs of termite activity in Top End homes. Mud tubes, drumming sound, sagging floors, frass piles, swarming alates — what to look for, what's an emergency, and what's normal.">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <link rel="canonical" href="https://darwintermitebarriers.com.au/signs-of-termites/">
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">9 specific things to look for</span>
      <h1>Signs of termites <span class="accent">in Top End homes</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Coptotermes acinaciformis tunnels invisibly through timber for years
        before any visible signs surface. Here are the nine signs that should
        trigger an inspection call &mdash; and the three that are emergency.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Urgent inspection</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Outside the house</span>
      <h2>External signs (5 of 9).</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>1. Mud tubes / leads.</h3>
        <p>
          Pencil-thick (3&ndash;8mm) tubes of soil, faeces and saliva running
          up external walls, foundation surfaces, or under-house piers. The
          most diagnostic sign of subterranean termites. <strong>EMERGENCY
          INDICATOR.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">2. Frass piles.</h3>
        <p>
          Small piles of pellet-like faeces below timber. Different species
          have different frass profiles &mdash; drywood termites leave coarser
          dark pellets, subterranean termites leave less obvious frass mixed
          with mud. Check window sills, door frames, deck timbers.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">3. Swarming alates.</h3>
        <p>
          During wet-season build-up (September&ndash;November in the Top End), reproductive
          termites swarm to start new colonies. Look for piles of discarded
          translucent wings on window sills, under outdoor lights, or near
          flying-insect screens. Indicates an established colony nearby (not
          necessarily your house yet).
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">4. Mud nests in trees / stumps.</h3>
        <p>
          Football-sized or larger mud nests in tree forks or old stumps in
          the yard. Often Coptotermes acinaciformis or Schedorhinotermes
          intermedius. A nest within 200m is feeding ground &mdash; your house
          is at risk.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">5. Damaged outdoor timber structures.</h3>
        <p>
          Check fences, retaining sleepers, decking. Tap with a hammer &mdash;
          a hollow sound where solid is expected indicates internal galleries.
          External skin often looks intact (termites eat from inside).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Inside the house</span>
      <h2>Internal signs (4 of 9).</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>6. Drumming or rattling sound from walls.</h3>
        <p>
          Soldier termites &ldquo;head-bang&rdquo; against gallery walls as an
          alarm signal when disturbed. You may hear faint papery rattling
          inside walls when tapping. Most audible at night when ambient noise
          is low. <strong>EMERGENCY INDICATOR.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">7. Sagging or buckling timber.</h3>
        <p>
          Skirting board pushed away from wall, architrave separating from
          door frame, floorboard sagging where it shouldn&rsquo;t. Termites
          have hollowed the timber from inside. Late-stage damage.
          <strong>EMERGENCY INDICATOR.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">8. Doors or windows suddenly tight.</h3>
        <p>
          A door or window that&rsquo;s been opening fine for years suddenly
          binds. Often because the surrounding frame is being eaten and is
          subtly shifting. Could also be normal seasonal movement &mdash; but
          if it&rsquo;s sudden, get it checked.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">9. Paint blistering or surface bubbling.</h3>
        <p>
          Paint on internal walls or door jambs blistering in a small patch.
          Termites have hollowed the timber substrate and moisture / heat is
          deforming the paint. Tap with hammer to confirm hollow sound.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The three &ldquo;call us today&rdquo; signs.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>If you see ANY of these, call within 24 hours:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Visible mud tubes / leads on the foundation or external walls.</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Drumming/rattling sound from walls at night.</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Sagging or buckling internal timber, especially around skirting and architraves.</strong></li>
        </ol>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          These indicate active colony involvement with the building structure.
          Delaying treatment by 6 months can mean structural repair instead
          of treatment alone.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>What NOT to do if you find signs.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t spray DIY insecticide.</strong> Termites scatter when disturbed by surface chemicals, making them harder to find AND splitting the colony into multiple feeding fronts.</li>
          <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t knock down the mud tubes.</strong> Leave them in place &mdash; they help us trace the entry route. Photograph and call.</li>
          <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t open up walls to &ldquo;see how bad it is&rdquo;.</strong> You&rsquo;ll destroy evidence and possibly speed colony scatter.</li>
          <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t accept &ldquo;urgent treatment&rdquo; on the day from a door-knock operator.</strong> Get an independent inspection report before any treatment quote.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Where we work.</h2>
      <div class="areas-grid">
        <a class="area-pill" href="/palmerston/">Palmerston</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/casuarina/">Casuarina</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/nightcliff/">Nightcliff</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/humpty-doo/">Humpty Doo</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/howard-springs/">Howard Springs</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/greater-darwin/">All Greater Darwin</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>See any of the 9 signs?</h2>
        <p>Same-day or next-day inspection available.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book urgent inspection</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
